You are working in the Large Australian Retailer Modernisation Prototype.

Project intent:

- This is a working interview prototype for Software Developer role.
- Frame it as a neutral Large Australian Retailer modernisation vertical slice.
- Optimise for reviewer clarity: runnable locally, easy to inspect, honest about boundaries.
- Never name or imply a real client, real retailer, real data source, or confidential system.
- Do not overclaim production readiness. Prefer "production-shaped", "adapter boundary", "future integration point", and "governance contract".

Repo shape:

- The real git repo root is lar-modernisation-prototype/.
- frontend/ owns Angular, Nx, pnpm, Playwright and frontend runtime config.
- backend/ owns the .NET solution, layered projects and tests.
- docs/ contains reviewer-facing handoff material.
- prototype-delivery-notes/ and position-description/ outside the repo are planning/interview notes, not app source.

Frontend rules:

- Use Angular/Nx idioms: apps/ for runnable apps and e2e, libs/ for reusable services, UI, tokens, assets and utils.
- App composition belongs in frontend/apps/transformation-console.
- Backend communication belongs in frontend/libs/services through typed DTOs and service methods.
- Shared UI belongs in frontend/libs/ui-library and must be exported from libs/ui-library/src/index.ts.
- Pure helpers belong in frontend/libs/utils and should stay Angular-free unless there is a clear reason.
- Use path aliases such as @lar/services, @lar/ui-library, @lar/ui-assets and @lar/utils.
- Prefer standalone Angular components with explicit input()/output() APIs, separate HTML/SCSS/spec files, and shallow host tests.
- Use the Health Design System CSS/classes as the base where applicable; add LAR-specific styling only for shell, operational density and local app needs.
- Keep token layering clear:
  1. libs/ui-tokens/src/styles.css
  2. libs/ui-library/src/theme/styles.css
  3. app/global styles
  4. route-specific layout styles
  5. component-specific styles
- Do not scatter colours, radii, shadows or focus styles through route pages. Add or reuse tokens.
- Keep the UI calm, dense, structured and task-oriented. This is an internal operational console, not a public landing page.
- Avoid card nesting. Use CardComponent carefully: repeated items or framed tools only.
- Keep forms accessible through existing form wrapper/input/select/radio/checkbox components.
- Every route should preserve one h1, landmarks, accessible names, visible focus, readable contrast and no text overflow.

Runtime config:

- Do not treat frontend/apps/transformation-console/public/assets/runtime-config.js as source of truth.
- Local/browser runtime config is generated from .env.local or LAR*FRONTEND*\* variables.
- Keep mock mode explicit and visually obvious in the shell.
- Mock API fixtures must stay aligned with backend contracts.
- Do not commit .env.local. Add new local-only keys to .env.local.example and document them.

Backend rules:

- Preserve the layered .NET shape:
  - Api: endpoints, health, CORS, rate limiting, correlation, dependency registration.
  - Application: query services, workflow services, DTOs and service interfaces.
  - Domain: entities and shared domain concepts.
  - Infrastructure: EF Core SQLite, repositories, DbContext and seed data.
  - tests: API, application and integration coverage.
- Keep endpoints thin. Business rules and query behavior belong in Application services.
- Keep persistence details in Infrastructure.
- Use deterministic SQLite seed data for local review unless explicitly asked to add another provider.
- Maintain correlation IDs, correlated problem responses and operations status behavior.
- Keep CORS, rate limiting and security headers explicit and configurable.
- Demo role auth is a prototype boundary, not production identity. Writes use X-LAR-DEMO-ROLE and supported roles Viewer, DeliveryLead and Admin.
- Do not imply JWT, SSO, Entra ID, row-level security, PCI compliance or production authorization exists unless implemented.

Contracts and workflows:

- Frontend DTOs, mock API fixtures and backend response shapes must stay aligned.
- Feature query contracts support search, status, paging and sort validation. Keep validation explicit and tested.
- Workflow reviews are real persisted write paths but still demo-auth protected.
- Automation is governance-first. Do not add model-provider claims before governance, evidence, human approval, risk and audit boundaries are clear.
- Model providers, prompt registries, evaluation harnesses and enterprise audit stores are future integration points unless implemented.

Quality gates:

- Standard gate: pnpm verify.
- Full packaging gate: pnpm verify:full.
- Frontend checks include format, lint, Angular typecheck, unit tests, production build and Playwright e2e where relevant.
- Backend checks include format, build and dotnet test.
- Add focused tests when behavior changes.
- Use Playwright for routed UI, keyboard access, accessibility, contrast, viewport overflow and workflow smoke coverage.
- Use backend unit/integration tests for service behavior, endpoint contracts, validation, security config and persistence.

Docs and reviewer handoff:

- Update README.md, docs/architecture.md, docs/decisions.md, docs/reviewer-runbook.md and docs/ci-deployment-notes.md when architecture, commands, runtime config, API surface, Docker, CI or prototype boundaries change.
- Keep docs technical and reviewer-friendly, not marketing copy.
- README should clearly answer: what this is, how to run it, how to verify it, what is real, what is simulated and what production-next would be.
- Keep screenshots intentional and refresh them only after runtime mode/content/theme are final.

Implementation style:

- Prefer small, reviewable vertical slices.
- Reuse existing components, tokens, services and helpers before creating new abstractions.
- Add abstraction only when repeated behavior has stabilized.
- Keep changes scoped. Do not rewrite unrelated files or planning notes.
- Check git status before editing and never overwrite user changes.
